Supervised vs Unsupervised

Methods so far focused on supervised learning

Now we'll look at some common unsupervised techniques

  • Principal Components Analysis (PCA)

    • PCA Regression

  • Clustering

    • K Means
    • Heirarchical

Unsupervised Learning

Note: No great way to check results of your model

  • There is no correct answer to look at with test data

  • Hope that patterns detected extend to future data but checking that is difficult

  • Overall, pretty subjective and generally considered exploratory

  • Don't make really important decisions unless you can find a way to verify results extend!

Principal Components

  • Principal Components Analysis (PCA) is a dimension reduction technique

  • If you have \(p\) variables, they contain some joint variability/correlation

  • PCA looks for linear combinations of those \(p\) variables that account for most of the variability

  • Usually can represent variability of the \(p\) variables by \(m<p\) PCs

  • Reduces # of variables from \(p\) to \(m\)

  • Can be useful for visualizations

  • Can use PCs as predictors in a regression model (PC Regression)

PCA Details

Goal: Obtain a linear combination of the variables that accounts for the largest amount of variability (location not important for variance, assume 0 mean for each predictor)

Find

\[z_{i1} = \phi_{11}x_{i1} + \phi_{21}x_{i2} + ... + \phi_{p1}x_{ip}\]

values so that the set of \(z's\) has the largest variance.

  • Must constrain \(\phi\) values, else could get arbitrarily large

  • Constraint: \(\sum_{j=1}^{p}\phi_{j1}^2 = 1\)

PCA Details

Function of interest (variability is just sum of squared since mean is 0)

\[\underset{\phi's}{max}\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}z_{i1}^2\mbox{ subject to } \sum_{j=1}^{p}\phi_{j1}^2 = 1\]

Once first PC found, now find next most variable linear combination

  • Constraint: Must be uncorrelated with 1st PC

  • Process continues until \(min(n-1, p)\) PCs are found

PCA Details

Solving for the PCs is equivalent to doing an eigenvalue decomposition on the covariance matrix!

  • Eigenvectors represent the "loadings" \(\phi's\)

    • Weight for each variables "importance" in the PC

    • Can be used to create interpretations of PCs

  • Eigenvalues represent how much of the variation exists on that PC

  • Largest eigenvalue (w/eigenvector) correspond to first PC

PCA Details

SDs - the square roots of the eigenvalues of the cov/corr matrix

Rotation - the variable loadings (close to 0 –> small weight in that PC)

Recap

  • Principal Components Analysis (PCA) is a dimension reduction technique

  • PCA looks for linear combinations of \(p\) variables that accounts for as much variability as possible

  • Reduces dimension of data from \(p\) to \(m\)

  • Choosing \(m\) is subjective!

  • Interpretation is subjective!

  • Scaling is needed (most of the time) since units will vastly change results

  • Can use as predictors in a regression (or other) model (PC Regression)
